03982nam a2200541Ia 9780292756090DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20162016txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927560907 a10.7560/7560832doi  a(DE-B1597)586871  a(OCoLC)1280942883  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPR830.P75bR63 2016eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a823.009/353223  aHG 6802rvk0(DE-625)rvk/49236:1 aRodden, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBetween Self and Society :bInner Worlds and Outer Limits in the British Psychological Novel /cJohn Rodden. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (235 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterary Modernism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Smollett’s Roderick Random -- tChapter Two. Godwin’s Caleb Williams -- tChapter Three. Hardy’s The Mayor of Casterbridge -- tChapter Four. Ford’s The Good Soldier -- tChapter Five. Lewis’s Tarr -- tChapter Six. Lawrence’s Women in Love -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween Self and Society explores the psychosocial dramas that galvanize six major British novels written between the eighteenth and twentieth centuries. The book challenges an influential misconception that has for too long hindered appreciation of the psychological novel. John Rodden argues that there should be no simplifying antithesis between psychological, “inner” conflicts (within the mind or “soul”) and institutional, “outer” conflicts (within family, class, community). Instead, it is the overarching, dramatic—yet often tortuous—relations between self and society that demand our attention. Rodden presents fresh interpretations of an eclectic group of prose fiction classics, including Tobias Smollett’s The Adventures of Roderick Random, William Godwin’s Caleb Williams, Thomas Hardy’s The Mayor of Casterbridge, Ford Madox Ford’s The Good Soldier, Wyndham Lewis’s Tarr, and D. H. Lawrence’s Women in Love. Far from being merely admirable experiments, let alone daring though interesting failures, these fictions are shown to possess aesthetic unity, stylistic consistency, and psychic force. Between Self and Society thus impels our careful reconsideration of novels that represent major artistic achievements, yet have been either unjustly neglected or appreciated in limiting ways that do injustice to their psychological aspects. Rodden’s vibrant discussion invites an upward revaluation of these works and encourages the full recognition of their value and significance in British literary history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEnglish fictionxPsychological aspects. 0aEnglish fictionxSocial aspects. 0aPsychological fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aPsychology in literature. 0aSocial psychology and literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75608340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292756090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292756090/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles